# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: erlang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:erlang/actor-model] The **actor model** in computer science is a mathematical model of concurrent computation that treats an *actor* as the basic building block of concurrent computation.
[src:erlang/actor-model] In response to a message it receives, an actor can: make local decisions, create more actors, send more messages, and determine how to respond to the next message received.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Actors may modify their own private state, but can only affect each other indirectly through messaging (removing the need for lock-based synchronization).
[src:erlang/actor-model] It has been used both as a framework for a theoretical understanding of computation and as the theoretical basis for several practical implementations of concurrent systems.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The relationship of the model to other work is discussed in actor model and process calculi.
[src:erlang/actor-model] According to Carl Hewitt, unlike previous models of computation, the actor model was inspired by physics, including general relativity and quantum mechanics.
[src:erlang/actor-model] It was also influenced by the programming languages Lisp, Simula, early versions of Smalltalk, capability-based systems, and packet switching.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Following Hewitt, Bishop, and Steiger's 1973 publication, Irene Greif developed an operational semantics for the actor model as part of her doctoral research.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Two years later, Henry Baker and Hewitt published a set of axiomatic laws for actor systems.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Other major milestones include William Clinger's 1981 dissertation introducing a denotational semantics based on power domains and Gul Agha's 1985 dissertation which further developed a transition-based semantic model complementary to Clinger's.
[src:erlang/actor-model] This resulted in the full development of actor model theory.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Research groups led by Chuck Seitz at California Institute of Technology (Caltech) and Bill Dally at MIT constructed computer architectures that further developed the message passing in the model.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The actor model adopts the philosophy that *everything is an actor*.
[src:erlang/actor-model] This is similar to the *everything is an object* philosophy used by some object-oriented programming languages.
[src:erlang/actor-model] There is no assumed sequence to the above actions and they could be carried out in parallel.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Decoupling the sender from communications sent was a fundamental advance of the actor model enabling asynchronous communication and control structures as patterns of passing messages.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Recipients of messages are identified by address, sometimes called "mailing address".
[src:erlang/actor-model] Thus an actor can only communicate with actors whose addresses it has.
[src:erlang/actor-model] It can obtain those from a message it receives, or if the address is for an actor it has itself created.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The actor model is characterized by inherent concurrency of computation within and among actors, dynamic creation of actors, inclusion of actor addresses in messages, and interaction only through direct asynchronous message passing with no restriction on message arrival order.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Over the years, several different formal systems have been developed which permit reasoning about systems in the actor model.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The actor model can be used as a framework for modeling, understanding, and reasoning about a wide range of concurrent systems.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The actor model is about the semantics of message passing.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Arguably, the first concurrent programs were interrupt handlers.
[src:erlang/actor-model] During the course of its normal operation a computer needed to be able to receive information from outside (characters from a keyboard, packets from a network, *etc*).
[src:erlang/actor-model] So when the information arrived the execution of the computer was *interrupted* and special code (called an interrupt handler) was called to put the information in a data buffer where it could be subsequently retrieved.
[src:erlang/actor-model] In the early 1960s, interrupts began to be used to simulate the concurrent execution of several programs on one processor.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Having concurrency with shared memory gave rise to the problem of concurrency control.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Originally, this problem was conceived as being one of mutual exclusion on a single computer.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra developed semaphores and later, between 1971 and 1973, Tony Hoare and Per Brinch Hansen developed monitors to solve the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:erlang/actor-model] However, neither of these solutions provided a programming language construct that encapsulated access to shared resources.
[src:erlang/actor-model] This encapsulation was later accomplished by the serializer construct ([Hewitt and Atkinson 1977, 1979] and [Atkinson 1980]).
[src:erlang/actor-model] Each computational step was from one global state of the computation to the next global state.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The global state approach was continued in automata theory for finite-state machines and push down stack machines, including their nondeterministic versions.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Such nondeterministic automata have the property of bounded nondeterminism; that is, if a machine always halts when started in its initial state, then there is a bound on the number of states in which it halts.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra further developed the nondeterministic global state approach.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Hewitt argued that the actor model should provide the guarantee of service.
[src:erlang/actor-model] In Dijkstra's model, although there could be an unbounded amount of time between the execution of sequential instructions on a computer, a (parallel) program that started out in a well defined state could terminate in only a bounded number of states [Dijkstra 1976].
[src:erlang/actor-model] Consequently, his model could not provide the guarantee of service.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Dijkstra argued that it was impossible to implement unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Hewitt argued otherwise: there is no bound that can be placed on how long it takes a computational circuit called an *arbiter* to settle (see metastability (electronics)).
[src:erlang/actor-model] The actor model features unbounded nondeterminism which was captured in a mathematical model by Will Clinger using domain theory.
[src:erlang/actor-model] In the actor model, there is no global state.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Messages in the actor model are not necessarily buffered.
[src:erlang/actor-model] This was a sharp break with previous approaches to models of concurrent computation.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The lack of buffering caused a great deal of misunderstanding at the time of the development of the actor model and is still a controversial issue.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Some researchers argued that the messages are buffered in the "ether" or the "environment".
[src:erlang/actor-model] Also, messages in the actor model are simply sent (like packets in IP); there is no requirement for a synchronous handshake with the recipient.
[src:erlang/actor-model] A natural development of the actor model was to allow addresses in messages.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Influenced by packet switched networks [1961 and 1964], Hewitt proposed the development of a new model of concurrent computation in which communications would not have any required fields at all: they could be empty.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Of course, if the sender of a communication desired a recipient to have access to addresses which the recipient did not already have, the address would have to be sent in the communication.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The original actor could accomplish this by sending a communication that includes the message it wishes to send, along with the address of the third actor that will handle the response.
[src:erlang/actor-model] This third actor that will handle the response is called the *resumption* (sometimes also called a continuation or stack frame).
[src:erlang/actor-model] When the recipient actor is ready to send a response, it sends the response message to the *resumption* actor address that was included in the original communication.
[src:erlang/actor-model] As opposed to the previous approach based on composing sequential processes, the actor model was developed as an inherently concurrent model.
[src:erlang/actor-model] In the actor model sequentiality was a special case that derived from concurrent computation as explained in actor model theory.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Hewitt argued against adding the requirement that messages must arrive in the order in which they are sent to the actor.
[src:erlang/actor-model] If output message ordering is desired, then it can be modeled by a queue actor that provides this functionality.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Such a queue actor would queue the messages that arrived so that they could be retrieved in FIFO order.
[src:erlang/actor-model] So if an actor `X` sent a message `M1` to an actor `Y`, and later `X` sent another message `M2` to `Y`, there is no requirement that `M1` arrives at `Y` before `M2`.
[src:erlang/actor-model] In this respect the actor model mirrors packet switching systems which do not guarantee that packets must be received in the order sent.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Not providing the order of delivery guarantee allows packet switching to buffer packets, use multiple paths to send packets, resend damaged packets, and to provide other optimizations.
[src:erlang/actor-model] For more example, actors are allowed to pipeline the processing of messages.
[src:erlang/actor-model] What this means is that in the course of processing a message `M1`, an actor can designate the behavior to be used to process the next message, and then in fact begin processing another message `M2` before it has finished processing `M1`.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Just because an actor is allowed to pipeline the processing of messages does not mean that it *must* pipeline the processing.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Whether a message is pipelined is an engineering tradeoff.
[src:erlang/actor-model] How would an external observer know whether the processing of a message by an actor has been pipelined?
[src:erlang/actor-model] There is no ambiguity in the definition of an actor created by the possibility of pipelining.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Of course, it is possible to perform the pipeline optimization incorrectly in some implementations, in which case unexpected behavior may occur.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Another important characteristic of the actor model is locality.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Locality means that in processing a message, an actor can send messages only to addresses that it receives in the message, addresses that it already had before it received the message, and addresses for actors that it creates while processing the message.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Also locality means that there is no simultaneous change in multiple locations.
[src:erlang/actor-model] In this way it differs from some other models of concurrency, *e.g.*, the Petri net model in which tokens are simultaneously removed from multiple locations and placed in other locations.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The idea of composing actor systems into larger ones is an important aspect of modularity that was developed in Gul Agha's doctoral dissertation, developed later by Gul Agha, Ian Mason, Scott Smith, and Carolyn Talcott.
[src:erlang/actor-model] A key innovation was the introduction of *behavior* specified as a mathematical function to express what an actor does when it processes a message, including specifying a new behavior to process the next message that arrives.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Behaviors provided a mechanism to mathematically model the sharing in concurrency.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Behaviors also freed the actor model from implementation details, *e.g.*, the Smalltalk-72 token stream interpreter.
[src:erlang/actor-model] However, the efficient implementation of systems described by the actor model require *extensive* optimization.
[src:erlang/actor-model] See Actor model implementation for details.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Other concurrency systems (*e.g.*, process calculi) can be modeled in the actor model using a two-phase commit protocol.
[src:erlang/actor-model] There is a *Computational Representation Theorem* in the actor model for systems which are closed in the sense that they do not receive communications from outside.
[src:erlang/actor-model] In this way, ${\mathtt {S}}$ can be mathematically characterized in terms of all its possible behaviors (including those involving unbounded nondeterminism).
[src:erlang/actor-model] A consequence of the above theorem is that a finite actor can nondeterministically respond with an uncountable number of different outputs.
[src:erlang/actor-model] One of the key motivations for the development of the actor model was to understand and deal with the control structure issues that arose in development of the Planner programming language.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Once the actor model was initially defined, an important challenge was to understand the power of the model relative to Robert Kowalski's thesis that "computation can be subsumed by deduction".
[src:erlang/actor-model] Hewitt argued that Kowalski's thesis turned out to be false for the concurrent computation in the actor model (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:erlang/actor-model] Nevertheless, attempts were made to extend logic programming to concurrent computation.
[src:erlang/actor-model] However, Hewitt and Agha [1991] claimed that the resulting systems were not deductive in the following sense: computational steps of the concurrent logic programming systems do not follow deductively from previous steps (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:erlang/actor-model] Recently, logic programming has been integrated into the actor model in a way that maintains logical semantics.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Migration in the actor model is the ability of actors to change locations.
[src:erlang/actor-model] *E.g.*, in his dissertation, Aki Yonezawa modeled a post office that customer actors could enter, change locations within while operating, and exit.
[src:erlang/actor-model] An actor that can migrate can be modeled by having a location actor that changes when the actor migrates.
[src:erlang/actor-model] However the faithfulness of this modeling is controversial and the subject of research.
[src:erlang/actor-model] A delicate point in the actor model is the ability to synthesize the address of an actor.
[src:erlang/actor-model] In some cases security can be used to prevent the synthesis of addresses (see Security).
[src:erlang/actor-model] However, if an actor address is simply a bit string then clearly it can be synthesized although it may be difficult or even infeasible to guess the address of an actor if the bit strings are long enough.
[src:erlang/actor-model] SOAP uses a URL for the address of an endpoint where an actor can be reached.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Since a URL is a character string, it can clearly be synthesized although encryption can make it virtually impossible to guess.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Synthesizing the addresses of actors is usually modeled using mapping.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The idea is to use an actor system to perform the mapping to the actual actor addresses.
[src:erlang/actor-model] For example, on a computer the memory structure of the computer can be modeled as an actor system that does the mapping.
[src:erlang/actor-model] In the case of SOAP addresses, it's modeling the DNS and the rest of the URL mapping.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Robin Milner's initial published work on concurrency was also notable in that it was not based on composing sequential processes.
[src:erlang/actor-model] His work differed from the actor model because it was based on a fixed number of processes of fixed topology communicating numbers and strings using synchronous communication.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Later versions of CSP abandoned communication based on process names in favor of anonymous communication via channels, an approach also used in Milner's work on the calculus of communicating systems (CCS) and the π-calculus.
[src:erlang/actor-model] These early models by Milner and Hoare both had the property of bounded nondeterminism.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Modern, theoretical CSP ([Hoare 1985] and [Roscoe 2005]) explicitly provides unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The actor model has been influential on both theory development and practical software development.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The actor model has influenced the development of the π-calculus and subsequent process calculi.
[src:erlang/actor-model] The actor model has had extensive influence on commercial practice.
[src:erlang/actor-model] For example, Twitter has used actors for scalability.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Also, Microsoft has used the actor model in the development of its Asynchronous Agents Library.
[src:erlang/actor-model] There are multiple other actor libraries listed in the actor libraries and frameworks section below.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Many of the ideas introduced in the actor model are now also finding application in multi-agent systems for these same reasons [Hewitt 2006b 2007b].
[src:erlang/actor-model] The key difference is that agent systems (in most definitions) impose extra constraints upon the actors, typically requiring that they make use of commitments and goals.
[src:erlang/actor-model] A number of different programming languages employ the actor model or some variation of it.
[src:erlang/actor-model] Actor libraries or frameworks have also been implemented to permit actor-style programming in languages that don't have actors built-in.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] One of the main reasons for using Erlang instead of other functional languages is Erlang's ability to handle concurrency and distributed programming.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] By concurrency is meant programs that can handle several threads of execution at the same time.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] For example, modern operating systems allow you to use a word processor, a spreadsheet, a mail client, and a print job all running at the same time.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Each processor (CPU) in the system is probably only handling one thread (or job) at a time, but it swaps between the jobs at such a rate that it gives the illusion of running them all at the same time.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] It is easy to create parallel threads of execution in an Erlang program and to allow these threads to communicate with each other.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] In Erlang, each thread of execution is called a *process*.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] (Aside: the term "process" is usually used when the threads of execution share no data with each other and the term "thread" when they share data in some way.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Threads of execution in Erlang share no data, that is why they are called processes).
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The Erlang BIF `spawn` is used to create a new process: `spawn(Module, Exported_Function, List of Arguments)`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] As shown, the function `say_something` writes its first argument the number of times specified by the second argument.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The function `start` starts two Erlang processes, one that writes "hello" three times and one that writes "goodbye" three times.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Both processes use the function `say_something`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Notice that a function used in this way by `spawn`, to start a process, must be exported from the module (that is, in the `-export` at the start of the module).
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Notice that it did not write "hello" three times and then "goodbye" three times.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Instead, the first process wrote a "hello", the second a "goodbye", the first another "hello" and so forth.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The return value of a function is the return value of the last "thing" in the function.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] `spawn` returns a *process identifier*, or *pid*, which uniquely identifies the process.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] So `<0.63.0>` is the pid of the `spawn` function call above.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Notice also that ~p is used instead of ~w in `io:format/2`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] In the following example two processes are created and they send messages to each other a number of times.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] `Pong_PID` is the process identity of the "pong" process.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] `<0.36.0>` is the return value from the `start` function.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The `receive` construct is used to allow processes to wait for messages from other processes.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Notice there is no ";" before the `end`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Messages between Erlang processes are simply valid Erlang terms.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] That is, they can be lists, tuples, integers, atoms, pids, and so on.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Each process has its own input queue for messages it receives.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] New messages received are put at the end of the queue.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] When a process executes a `receive`, the first message in the queue is matched against the first pattern in the `receive`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If this matches, the message is removed from the queue and the actions corresponding to the pattern are executed.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] However, if the first pattern does not match, the second pattern is tested.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If this matches, the message is removed from the queue and the actions corresponding to the second pattern are executed.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If the second pattern does not match, the third is tried and so on until there are no more patterns to test.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If there are no more patterns to test, the first message is kept in the queue and the second message is tried instead.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If this matches any pattern, the appropriate actions are executed and the second message is removed from the queue (keeping the first message and any other messages in the queue).
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If the second message does not match, the third message is tried, and so on, until the end of the queue is reached.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If the end of the queue is reached, the process blocks (stops execution) and waits until a new message is received and this procedure is repeated.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The Erlang implementation is "clever" and minimizes the number of times each message is tested against the patterns in each `receive`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If the atom `finished` is received, "pong" writes "Pong finished" to the output and, as it has nothing more to do, terminates.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Notice how the operator `!` is used to send messages.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] That is, `Message` (any Erlang term) is sent to the process with identity `Pid`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] After sending the message `pong` to the process "ping", "pong" calls the `pong` function again, which causes it to get back to the `receive` again and wait for another message.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Looking at the function `ping/2`, the second clause of `ping/2` is executed since the value of the first argument is 3 (not 0) (first clause head is `ping(0,Pong_PID)`, second clause head is `ping(N,Pong_PID)`, so `N` becomes 3).
[src:erlang/conc-prog] `self/0` returns the pid of the process that executes `self/0`, in this case the pid of "ping".
[src:erlang/conc-prog] It writes "Ping received pong" when this reply arrives, after which "ping" calls the `ping` function again.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] `N-1` causes the first argument to be decremented until it becomes 0.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The atom `finished` is sent to "pong" (causing it to terminate as described above) and "ping finished" is written to the output.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] "Ping" then terminates as it has nothing left to do.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] In the above example, "pong" was first created to be able to give the identity of "pong" when "ping" was started.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] That is, in some way "ping" must be able to know the identity of "pong" to be able to send a message to it.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Sometimes processes which need to know each other's identities are started independently of each other.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Erlang thus provides a mechanism for processes to be given names so that these names can be used as identities instead of pids.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] both spawns the "pong" process and gives it the name `pong`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] `ping/2` now becomes `ping/1` as the argument `Pong_PID` is not needed.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Let us rewrite the ping pong program with "ping" and "pong" on different computers.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] First a few things need to be set up to get this to work.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The distributed Erlang implementation provides a very basic authentication mechanism to prevent unintentional access to an Erlang system on another computer.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Erlang systems which talk to each other must have the same *magic cookie*.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The `.erlang.cookie` file is to contain a line with the same atom.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The `chmod` above makes the `.erlang.cookie` file accessible only by the owner of the file.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If you want to experiment with distributed Erlang, but you only have one computer to work on, you can start two separate Erlang systems on the same computer but give them different names.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Each Erlang system running on a computer is called an *Erlang node*.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Let us assume there are two computers called gollum and kosken.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] First a node is started on kosken, called ping, and then a node on gollum, called pong.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] As shown, the ping pong program has run.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Thus, Erlang pids contain information about where the process executes.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] So if you know the pid of a process, the `!` operator can be used to send it a message disregarding if the process is on the same node or on a different node.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] A tuple `{registered_name,node_name}` is used instead of just the `registered_name`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] In the previous example, "ping" and "pong" were started from the shells of two separate Erlang nodes.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] `spawn` can also be used to start processes in other nodes.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Notice that all the output is received on gollum.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] This is because the I/O system finds out where the process is spawned from and sends all output there.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Now for a larger example with a simple "messenger".
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The messenger is a program that allows users to log in on different nodes and send simple messages to each other.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The messenger is set up by allowing "clients" to connect to a central server and say who and where they are.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] That is, a user does not need to know the name of the Erlang node where another user is located to send a message.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] In the following example using this program, nodes are started on four different computers.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If you do not have that many machines available on your network, you can start several nodes on the same machine.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Four Erlang nodes are started up: messenger@super, c1@bilbo, c2@kosken, c3@gollum.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] But this fails as Fred has already logged off.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] First let us look at some of the new concepts that have been introduced.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] There are two versions of the `server_transfer` function: one with four arguments (`server_transfer/4`) and one with five (`server_transfer/5`).
[src:erlang/conc-prog] These are regarded by Erlang as two separate functions.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Notice how to write the `server` function so that it calls itself, through `server(User_List)`, and thus creates a loop.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The Erlang compiler is "clever" and optimizes the code so that this really is a sort of loop and not a proper function call.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] But this only works if there is no code after the call.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Otherwise, the compiler expects the call to return and make a proper function call.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] This would result in the process getting bigger and bigger for every loop.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Functions in the `lists` module are used.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] This is a very useful module and a study of the manual page is recommended (`erl -man lists`).
[src:erlang/conc-prog] `lists:keymember(Key,Position,List)` looks through a list of tuples and looks at `Position` in each tuple to see if it is the same as `Key`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If it finds a tuple where the element at `Position` is the same as `Key`, it returns `true`, otherwise `false`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] `lists:keyfind` is like `lists:keymember`, but it returns `Tuple_Found` or the atom `false`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] There are many very useful functions in the `lists` module.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] An Erlang process (conceptually) runs until it does a `receive` and there is no message which it wants to receive in the message queue.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] "conceptually" is used here because the Erlang system shares the CPU time between the active processes in the system.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] A process terminates when there is nothing more for it to do, that is, the last function it calls simply returns and does not call another function.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Another way for a process to terminate is for it to call `exit/1`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The argument to `exit/1` has a special meaning, which is discussed later.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] In this example, `exit(normal)` is done, which has the same effect as a process running out of functions to call.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] The BIF `whereis(RegisteredName)` checks if a registered process of name `RegisteredName` exists.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If it exists, the pid of that process is returned.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If it does not exist, the atom `undefined` is returned.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] You should by now be able to understand most of the code in the messenger-module.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Let us study one case in detail: a message is sent from one user to another.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] This is received by the client, which in turn does `exit(normal)` and terminates.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] If `keyfind` returns `{From,Name}` it is certain that the user is logged on and that their name (peter) is in the variable `Name`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Notice that as this is `server_transfer/5`, it is not the same as the previous function `server_transfer/4`.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] This time argument 2 is used, which is the second element in the tuple.
[src:erlang/conc-prog] Peter's client receives the message in the `await_result` function.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The Erlang programming language has data, pattern matching, and functional programming.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The sequential subset of the Erlang language supports eager evaluation, single assignment, and dynamic typing.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] A normal Erlang application is built out of hundreds of small Erlang processes.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] It was originally proprietary software within Ericsson, developed by Joe Armstrong, Robert Virding, and Mike Williams in 1986, but was released as free and open-source software in 1998.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang/OTP is supported and maintained by the Open Telecom Platform (OTP) product unit at Ericsson.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The name *Erlang*, attributed to Bjarne Däcker, has been presumed by those working on the telephony switches (for whom the language was designed) to be a reference to Danish mathematician and engineer Agner Krarup Erlang and a syllabic abbreviation of "Ericsson Language".
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang was designed with the aim of improving the development of telephony applications.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The initial version of Erlang was implemented in Prolog and was influenced by the programming language PLEX used in earlier Ericsson exchanges.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] By 1988 Erlang had proven that it was suitable for prototyping telephone exchanges, but the Prolog interpreter was far too slow.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] One group within Ericsson estimated that it would need to be 40 times faster to be suitable for production use.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] In 1992, work began on the BEAM virtual machine (VM), which compiles Erlang to C using a mix of natively compiled code and threaded code to strike a balance between performance and disk space.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] According to co-inventor Joe Armstrong, the language went from laboratory product to real applications following the collapse of the next-generation AXE telephone exchange named *AXE-N* in 1995.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] As a result, Erlang was chosen for the next Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) exchange *AXD*.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] In February 1998, Ericsson Radio Systems banned the in-house use of Erlang for new products, citing a preference for non-proprietary languages.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The ban caused Armstrong and others to make plans to leave Ericsson.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] In March 1998 Ericsson announced the AXD301 switch, containing over a million lines of Erlang and reported to achieve a high availability of nine "9"s.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] In December 1998, the implementation of Erlang was open-sourced and most of the Erlang team resigned to form a new company, Bluetail AB.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Ericsson eventually relaxed the ban and re-hired Armstrong in 2004.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] In 2006, native symmetric multiprocessing support was added to the runtime system and VM.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang applications are built of very lightweight Erlang processes in the Erlang runtime system.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The Erlang runtime system provides strict process isolation between Erlang processes (this includes data and garbage collection, separated individually by each Erlang process) and transparent communication between processes (see Location transparency) on different Erlang nodes (on different hosts).
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] In 2014, Ericsson reported Erlang was being used in its support nodes, and in GPRS, 3G and LTE mobile networks worldwide and also by Nortel and Deutsche Telekom.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is the programming language used to code WhatsApp.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] It is also the language of choice for Ejabberd – an XMPP messaging server.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Elixir is a programming language that compiles into BEAM byte code (via Erlang Abstract Format).
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Since being released as open source, Erlang has been spreading beyond telecoms, establishing itself in other vertical markets such as FinTech, gaming, healthcare, automotive, Internet of Things and blockchain.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Apart from WhatsApp, there are other companies listed as Erlang's success stories, including Vocalink (a MasterCard company), Goldman Sachs, Nintendo, AdRoll, Grindr, BT Mobile, Samsung, OpenX, and SITA.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Omitting the comments gives a much shorter program.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The above example recursively invokes the function `qsort` until nothing remains to be sorted.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The expression `[Front || Front <- Rest, Front < Pivot]` is a list comprehension, meaning "Construct a list of elements `Front` such that `Front` is a member of `Rest`, and `Front` is less than `Pivot`." `++` is the list concatenation operator.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] A comparison function can be used for more complicated structures for the sake of readability.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] A `Pivot` is taken from the first parameter given to `qsort()` and the rest of `Lists` is named `Rest`.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The anonymous function is named `Smaller` in the parameter list of the second definition of `qsort` so that it can be referenced by that name within that function.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] It is not named in the first definition of `qsort`, which deals with the base case of an empty list and thus has no need of this function, let alone a name for it.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Integers are written as sequences of decimal digits, for example, 12, 12375 and -23427 are integers.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Integer arithmetic is exact and only limited by available memory on the machine.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Atoms are used within a program to denote distinguished values.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] They are written as strings of consecutive alphanumeric characters, the first character being lowercase.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Atoms can contain any character if they are enclosed within single quotes and an escape convention exists which allows any character to be used within an atom.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Atoms are never garbage collected and should be used with caution, especially if using dynamic atom generation.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] References are globally unique symbols whose only property is that they can be compared for equality.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Binaries provide a space-efficient way of storing binary data.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang primitives exist for composing and decomposing binaries and for efficient input/output of binaries.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Pids are references to Erlang processes.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Ports are used to communicate with the external world.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Tuples are containers for a fixed number of Erlang data types.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The arguments can be primitive data types or compound data types.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Any element of a tuple can be accessed in constant time.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Lists are containers for a variable number of Erlang data types.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The first element of a list can be accessed in constant time.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Maps contain a variable number of key-value associations.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Strings are written as doubly quoted lists of characters.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] code points for the characters in the string.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Records provide a convenient way for associating a tag with each of the elements in a tuple.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] This allows one to refer to an element of a tuple by name and not by position.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] A pre-compiler takes the record definition and replaces it with the appropriate tuple reference.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is designed with a mechanism that makes it easy for external processes to monitor for crashes (or hardware failures), rather than an in-process mechanism like exception handling used in many other programming languages.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Crashes are reported like other messages, which is the only way processes can communicate with each other, and subprocesses can be spawned cheaply (see below).
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The "let it crash" philosophy prefers that a process be completely restarted rather than trying to recover from a serious failure.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Though it still requires handling of errors, this philosophy results in less code devoted to defensive programming where error-handling code is highly contextual and specific.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] A typical Erlang application is written in the form of a supervisor tree.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] This architecture is based on a hierarchy of processes in which the top level process is known as a "supervisor".
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The supervisor then spawns multiple child processes that act either as workers or more, lower level supervisors.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Such hierarchies can exist to arbitrary depths and have proven to provide a highly scalable and fault-tolerant environment within which application functionality can be implemented.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Within a supervisor tree, all supervisor processes are responsible for managing the lifecycle of their child processes, and this includes handling situations in which those child processes crash.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Any process can become a supervisor by first spawning a child process, then calling `erlang:monitor/2` on that process.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] If the monitored process then crashes, the supervisor will receive a message containing a tuple whose first member is the atom `'DOWN'`.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The supervisor is responsible firstly for listening for such messages and for taking the appropriate action to correct the error condition.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang's main strength is support for concurrency.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] It has a small but powerful set of primitives to create processes and communicate among them.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is conceptually similar to the language occam, though it recasts the ideas of communicating sequential processes (CSP) in a functional framework and uses asynchronous message passing.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Processes are the primary means to structure an Erlang application.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] They are neither operating system processes nor threads, but lightweight processes that are scheduled by BEAM.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Like operating system processes (but unlike operating system threads), they share no state with each other.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The estimated minimal overhead for each is 300 words.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Thus, many processes can be created without degrading performance.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] In 2005, a benchmark with 20 million processes was successfully performed with 64-bit Erlang on a machine with 16 GB random-access memory (RAM; total 800 bytes/process).
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang has supported symmetric multiprocessing since release R11B of May 2006.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] While threads need external library support in most languages, Erlang provides language-level features to create and manage processes with the goal of simplifying concurrent programming.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Though all concurrency is explicit in Erlang, processes communicate using message passing instead of shared variables, which removes the need for explicit locks (a locking scheme is still used internally by the VM).
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Inter-process communication works via a shared-nothing asynchronous message passing system: every process has a "mailbox", a queue of messages that have been sent by other processes and not yet consumed.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] A process uses the `receive` primitive to retrieve messages that match desired patterns.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] A message-handling routine tests messages in turn against each pattern, until one of them matches.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] When the message is consumed and removed from the mailbox the process resumes execution.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] A message may comprise any Erlang structure, including primitives (integers, floats, characters, atoms), tuples, lists, and functions.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] As the example shows, processes may be created on remote nodes, and communication with them is transparent in the sense that communication with remote processes works exactly as communication with local processes.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Concurrency supports the primary method of error-handling in Erlang.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] When a process crashes, it neatly exits and sends a message to the controlling process which can then take action, such as starting a new process that takes over the old process's task.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The official reference implementation of Erlang uses BEAM.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] BEAM is included in the official distribution of Erlang, called Erlang/OTP.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] BEAM executes bytecode which is converted to threaded code at load time.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] It also includes a native code compiler on most platforms, developed by the High Performance Erlang Project (HiPE) at Uppsala University.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Since October 2001 the HiPE system is fully integrated in Ericsson's Open Source Erlang/OTP system.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] It also supports interpreting, directly from source code via abstract syntax tree, via script as of R11B-5 release of Erlang.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang supports language-level Dynamic Software Updating.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] To implement this, code is loaded and managed as "module" units; the module is a compilation unit.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The system can keep two versions of a module in memory at the same time, and processes can concurrently run code from each.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The versions are referred to as the "new" and the "old" version.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] A process will not move into the new version until it makes an external call to its module.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] For the second version, we add the possibility to reset the count to zero.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Only when receiving a message consisting of the atom `code_switch` will the loop execute an external call to codeswitch/1 (`?MODULE` is a preprocessor macro for the current module).
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] If there is a new version of the *counter* module in memory, then its codeswitch/1 function will be called.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] The practice of having a specific entry-point into a new version allows the programmer to transform state to what is needed in the newer version.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] In the example, the state is kept as an integer.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] In practice, systems are built up using design principles from the Open Telecom Platform, which leads to more code upgradable designs.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Successful hot code loading is exacting.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Code must be written with care to make use of Erlang's facilities.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] In 1998, Ericsson released Erlang as free and open-source software to ensure its independence from a single vendor and to increase awareness of the language.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang, together with libraries and the real-time distributed database Mnesia, forms the OTP collection of libraries.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Ericsson and a few other companies support Erlang commercially.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Since the open source release, Erlang has been used by several firms worldwide, including Nortel and Deutsche Telekom.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Although Erlang was designed to fill a niche and has remained an obscure language for most of its existence, its popularity is growing due to demand for concurrent services.
[src:erlang/erlang-programming-language] Erlang has found some use in fielding massively multiplayer online role-playing game (MMORPG) servers.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Most operating systems have a command interpreter or shell.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Windows has the command prompt, PowerShell, and more.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Erlang has its own shell where you can write and evaluate bits of Erlang code directly (see the `shell` manual page in STDLIB).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Start the Erlang shell (in Linux or UNIX) by starting a shell or command interpreter in your operating system and typing `erl`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Type `2 + 5.` in the shell and then press Enter (carriage return).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice that you tell the shell you are done entering code by finishing with a full stop `.` and a carriage return.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] As shown, the Erlang shell numbers the lines that can be entered (as `1>`, `2>`, ...) and correctly says that 2 + 5 is 7.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] If you make writing mistakes in the shell, you can delete with the backspace key, as in most shells.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] There are many more editing commands in the shell (see tty - A command line interface in ERTS User's Guide).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] (Notice that many line numbers given by the shell in the following examples are out of sequence.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This is because this tutorial was written and code-tested in separate sessions).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice the use of brackets, the multiplication operator `*`, and the division operator `/`, as in normal arithmetic (see Expressions).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Press Control-C to shut down the Erlang system and the Erlang shell.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] A programming language is not much use if you can only run code from the shell.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Enter it into a file named `tut.erl` using a suitable text editor.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The file name `tut.erl` is important, and also that it is in the same directory as the one where you started `erl`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] If you are lucky, your editor has an Erlang mode that makes it easier for you to enter and format your code nicely (see The Erlang mode for Emacs in Tools User's Guide), but you can manage perfectly well without.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] It is not hard to guess that this program doubles the value of numbers.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The first two lines of the code are described later.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The `{ok,tut}` means that the compilation is OK.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] If it says `error` it means that there is some mistake in the text that you entered.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Additional error messages give an idea about what is wrong so you can modify the text and then try to compile the program again.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Now let us get back to the first two lines of the code.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice the full stop `.` at the end of the line.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The files which are used to store the module must have the same name as the module but with the extension `.erl`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] In this case the file name is `tut.erl`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] When using a function in another module, the syntax `module_name:function_name(arguments)` is used.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] So the following means call function `double` in module `tut` with argument `10`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The second line also says that this function can be called from outside the module `tut`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Again, notice the `.` at the end of the line.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Now for a more complicated example, the factorial of a number.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] For example, the factorial of 4 is `4 * 3 * 2 * 1`, which equals 24.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] So this is a module called `tut1` that contains a function called `fac`, which takes one argument, `N`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice that this part ends with a semicolon `;` that indicates that there is more of the function `fac` to come.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice that this part ends with a `.` saying that there are no more parts of this function.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Here the function `fac` in module `tut1` is called with argument `4`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice that it is also required to expand the `-export` line with the information that there is another function `mult` with two arguments.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] In this example the numbers are integers and the arguments in the functions in the code `N`, `X`, and `Y` are called variables.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Variables must start with a capital letter (see Variables).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Examples of variables are `Number`, `ShoeSize`, and `Age`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Atoms start with a lowercase letter (see Atom), for example, `charles`, `centimeter`, and `inch`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] They are not like variables, which can have a value.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Enter the next program in a file named `tut2.erl`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice the introduction of decimals (floating point numbers) without any explanation.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The two parts of the `convert` function are called its clauses.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] As shown, `miles` is not part of either of the clauses.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The Erlang system cannot *match* either of the clauses so an error message `function_clause` is returned.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Now the `tut2` program is hardly good programming style.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Or does it mean that 3 is in centimeters and is to be converted to inches?
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Erlang has a way to group things together to make things more understandable.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] These are called *tuples* and are surrounded by curly brackets, `{` and `}`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] So, `{inch,3}` denotes 3 inches and `{centimeter,5}` denotes 5 centimeters.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Now let us write a new program that converts centimeters to inches and conversely.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice on line 16 that 5 inches are converted to centimeters and back again, yielding the original value.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This also shows that the argument to a function can be the result of another function.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The argument given to the function `{inch,5}` is first matched against the first head clause of `convert_length`, that is, `convert_length({centimeter,X})`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] It can be seen that `{centimeter,X}` does not match `{inch,5}` (the head is the bit before the `->`).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This having failed, let us try the head of the next clause that is, `convert_length({inch,Y})`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Tuples can have more than two parts, in fact as many parts as you want, and contain any valid Erlang *term*.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Tuples have a fixed number of items in them.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Each item in a tuple is called an *element*.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Here `c` represents Celsius and `f` Fahrenheit.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Whereas tuples group things together, it is also necessary to represent lists of things.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Lists in Erlang are surrounded by square brackets, `[` and `]`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice that this list was so long that it did not fit on one line.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This does not matter, Erlang allows line breaks at all "sensible places" but not, for example, in the middle of atoms, integers, and others.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] A useful way of looking at parts of lists is by using `|`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] To separate the first element of the list from the rest of the list, `|` is used.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Here you see the use of `|` to get the first two elements from the list.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] If you try to get more elements from the list than there are elements in the list, an error is returned.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] In the previous examples, new variable names are used, instead of reusing the old ones: `First`, `TheRest`, `E1`, `E2`, `R`, `A`, `B`, and `C`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The reason for this is that a variable can only be given a value once in its context (scope).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The following example shows how to find the length of a list.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The length of an empty list is obviously 0.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The length of a list with the first element `First` and the remaining elements `Rest` is 1 + the length of `Rest`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] In general, tuples are used where "records" or "structs" are used in other languages.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Also, lists are used when representing things with varying sizes, that is, where linked lists are used in other languages.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Erlang does not have a string data type.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Instead, strings can be represented by lists of Unicode characters.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This implies for example that the list `[97,98,99]` is equivalent to `"abc"`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Maps are a set of key to value associations.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] These associations are encapsulated with `#{` and `}`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Let us jump straight into the deep end with an example using some interesting features.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The following example shows how to calculate alpha blending using maps to reference color and alpha channels.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] First a macro `is_channel` is defined to help with the guard tests.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This is only here for convenience and to reduce syntax cluttering.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] For more information about macros, see The Preprocessor.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The function `new/4` creates a new map term and lets the keys `red`, `green`, `blue`, and `alpha` be associated with an initial value.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] In this case, only float values between and including 0.0 and 1.0 are allowed, as ensured by the `?is_channel/1` macro for each argument.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Only the `=>` operator is allowed when creating a new map.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] By calling `blend/2` on any color term created by `new/4`, the resulting color can be calculated as determined by the two map terms.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The value associated with key `alpha` is fetched for both arguments using the `:=` operator.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The other keys in the map are ignored, only the key `alpha` is required and checked for.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This is also the case for functions `red/2`, `blue/2`, and `green/2`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The difference here is that a check is made for two keys in each map argument.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The `Dst` map is updated with new channel values.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The syntax for updating an existing key with a new value is with the `:=` operator.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Erlang has many standard modules to help you do things.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] For example, the module `io` contains many functions that help in doing formatted input/output.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] To look up information about standard modules, the command `h(..)` can be used at the Erlang shell.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] If this does not work on your system, the documentation is included as HTML in the Erlang/OTP release.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] You can also read the documentation as HTML or download it as epub from <www.erlang.org/doc>.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] It is nice to be able to do formatted output in examples, so the next example shows a simple way to use the `io:format/2` function.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The function `io:format/2` (that is, `format` with two arguments) takes two lists.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The first one is nearly always a list written between `" "`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This list is printed out as it is, except that each `~w` is replaced by a term taken in order from the second list.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The `io:format/2` function itself returns the atom `ok` if everything goes as planned.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Like other functions in Erlang, it crashes if an error occurs.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This is not a fault in Erlang, it is a deliberate policy.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Erlang has sophisticated mechanisms to handle errors which are shown later.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] As an exercise, try to make `io:format/2` crash, it should not be difficult.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] But notice that although `io:format/2` crashes, the Erlang shell itself does not crash.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Now for a larger example to consolidate what you have learnt so far.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Assume that you have a list of temperature readings from a number of cities in the world.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Some of them are in Celsius and some in Fahrenheit (as in the previous list).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] First let us convert them all to Celsius, then let us print the data neatly.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Before looking at how this program works, notice that a few comments are added to the code.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] A comment starts with a %-character and goes on to the end of the line.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice also that the `-export([format_temps/1]).` line only includes the function `format_temps/1`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The other functions are *local* functions, that is, they are not visible from outside the module `tut5`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice also that when testing the program from the shell, the input is spread over two lines as the line was too long.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] When `format_temps` is called the first time, `City` gets the value `{moscow,{c,-10}}` and `Rest` is the rest of the list.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] So the function `print_temp(convert_to_celsius({moscow,{c,-10}}))` is called.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Here is a function call with `convert_to_celsius({moscow,{c,-10}})` as the argument to the function `print_temp`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] When function calls are *nested* like this, they execute (evaluate) from the inside out.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] That is, first `convert_to_celsius({moscow,{c,-10}})` is evaluated, which gives the value `{moscow,{c,-10}}` as the temperature is already in Celsius.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The function `convert_to_celsius` works in a similar way to the `convert_length` function in the previous example.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] `print_temp` simply calls `io:format` in a similar way to what has been described above.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice that `~-15w` says to print the "term" with a field length (width) of 15 and left justify it.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] (see `io:fwrite/1` manual page in STDLIB).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Now `format_temps(Rest)` is called with the rest of the list as an argument.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This way of doing things is similar to the loop constructs in other languages.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] (Yes, this is recursion, but do not let that worry you.) So the same `format_temps` function is called again, this time `City` gets the value `{cape_town,{f,70}}` and the same procedure is repeated as before.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This is done until the list becomes empty, that is [], which causes the first clause `format_temps([])` to match.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This simply returns (results in) the atom `ok`, so the program ends.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] It can be useful to find the maximum and minimum temperature in lists like this.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] First notice that two functions have the same name, `list_max`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] However, each of these takes a different number of arguments (parameters).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] In Erlang these are regarded as completely different functions.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Where you need to distinguish between these functions, you write Name/Arity, where Name is the function name and Arity is the number of arguments, in this case `list_max/1` and `list_max/2`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] In this example you walk through a list "carrying" a value, in this case `Result_so_far`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] `list_max/1` simply assumes that the max value of the list is the head of the list and calls `list_max/2` with the rest of the list and the value of the head of the list.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] If you tried to use `list_max/1` with an empty list or tried to use it with something that is not a list at all, you would cause an error.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice that the Erlang philosophy is not to handle errors of this type in the function in which they occur, but to do so elsewhere.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] In `list_max/2`, you walk down the list and use `Head` instead of `Result_so_far` when `Head` > `Result_so_far`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] `when` is a special word used before the -> in the function to say that you only use this part of the function if the test that follows is true.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] If the guard is false (that is, the guard fails), the next part of the function is tried.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] In this case, if `Head` is not greater than `Result_so_far`, then it must be smaller or equal to it.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This means that a guard on the next part of the function is not needed.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] To change the above program to one that works out the minimum value of the elements in a list, you only need to write `<` instead of `>`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Earlier it was mentioned that a variable can only be given a value once in its scope.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] In the above you see that `Result_so_far` is given several values.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This is OK since every time you call `list_max/2` you create a new scope and one can regard `Result_so_far` as a different variable in each scope.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Another way of creating and giving a variable a value is by using the match operator `=`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] So if you write `M = 5`, a variable called `M` is created with the value `5`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] If, in the same scope, you then write `M = 6`, an error is returned.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The use of the match operator is particularly useful for pulling apart Erlang terms and creating new ones.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Here `X` gets the value `paris` and `Y` the value `{f,28}`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Variables can also be used to improve the readability of programs.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The module `lists` contains many functions for manipulating lists, for example, for reversing them.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] So before writing a list-manipulating function it is a good idea to check if one has not already been written for you (see the `lists` manual page in STDLIB).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Now let us get back to the cities and temperatures, but take a more structured approach this time.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Here `format_temps/1` calls `convert_list_to_c/1`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] `convert_list_to_c/1` takes off the head of the `List_of_cities`, converts it to Celsius if needed.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Now a function has to be added to find the cities with the maximum and minimum temperatures.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The following program is not the most efficient way of doing this as you walk through the list of cities four times.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] But it is better to first strive for clarity and correctness and to make programs efficient only if needed.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The function `find_max_and_min` works out the maximum and minimum temperature.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] A new construct, `if`, is introduced here.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice that there is no `;` before `end`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Conditions do the same as guards, that is, tests that succeed or fail.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Erlang starts at the top and tests until it finds a condition that succeeds.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Then it evaluates (performs) the action following the condition and ignores all other conditions and actions before the `end`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] If no condition matches, a run-time failure occurs.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] A condition that always succeeds is the atom `true`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This is often used last in an `if`, meaning, do the action following the `true` if all other conditions have failed.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The following is a short program to show the workings of `if`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Notice that `tut9:test_if(33,33)` does not cause any condition to succeed.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This leads to the run time error `if_clause`, here nicely formatted by the shell.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] See Guard Sequences for details of the many guard tests available.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Both `case` and `if` have *return values*, that is, in the above example `case` returned either `{inch,X/2.54}` or `{centimeter,Y*2.54}`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The behaviour of `case` can also be modified by using guards.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] It tells us the length of a month, given the year.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The year must be known, since February has 29 days in a leap year.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] BIFs are functions that for some reason are built-in to the Erlang virtual machine.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] BIFs often implement functionality that is impossible or is too inefficient to implement in Erlang.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Some BIFs can be called using the function name only, but by default they belong to the `erlang` module.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] For example, the call to the BIF `trunc` below is equivalent to a call to `erlang:trunc`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] As shown, first it is checked if a year is leap.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] If a year is divisible by 400, it is a leap year.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] To determine this, first divide the year by 400 and use the BIF `trunc` (more about this later) to cut off any decimals.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Then multiply by 400 again and see if the same value is returned again.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] 2000 is not the same as 2004, so 2004 is not divisible by 400.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The next two `trunc`-tests evaluate if the year is divisible by 100 or 4 in the same way.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The first `if` returns `leap` or `not_leap`, which ends up in the variable `Leap`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This variable is used in the guard for `feb` in the following `case` that tells us how long the month is.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] There are many other BIFs such as `trunc`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Only a few BIFs can be used in guards, and you cannot use functions you have defined yourself in guards.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] These three BIFs do conversions that would be difficult (or impossible) to do in Erlang.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Erlang, like most modern functional programming languages, has higher-order functions.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Here a function that doubles the value of a number is defined and assigned to a variable.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] These two functions are provided in the standard library module `lists`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] `foreach` takes a list and applies a fun to every element in the list.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] `map` creates a new list by applying a fun to every element in a list.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Let us now define a fun that can be used to go through a list of cities and temperatures and transform them all to Celsius.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] When a function defined elsewhere is used as a fun, it can be referred to as `fun Function/Arity` (remember that `Arity` = number of arguments).
[src:erlang/seq-prog] That is why `fun convert_to_c/1` can be used in the call above.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] As shown, `convert_list_to_c` becomes much shorter and easier to understand.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] The standard module `lists` also contains a function `sort(Fun, List)` where `Fun` is a fun with two arguments.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This fun returns `true` if the first argument is less than the second argument, or else `false`.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] Here the concept of an *anonymous variable* `_` is introduced.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This is simply shorthand for a variable that gets a value, but the value is ignored.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] This can be used anywhere suitable, not just in funs.
[src:erlang/seq-prog] `Temp1 < Temp2` returns `true` if `Temp1` is less than `Temp2`.
